EASY EXAM STEPS – WEEK 10 LAB (MINIKUBE + NAGIOS + AWS)

This text file is designed so even a beginner with zero knowledge can
follow and perform tasks in the exam.

  ----------------------------------------
  SECTION 1: MINIKUBE (KUBERNETES) SETUP
  ----------------------------------------

STEP 1: CHECK REQUIREMENTS

You need: 1. Virtualization ON in BIOS (usually already enabled in most
laptops) 2. Install Docker Desktop OR VirtualBox OR Hyper-V

If using Windows: - Install Docker Desktop (recommended)

STEP 2: DOWNLOAD AND INSTALL MINIKUBE

1.  Open PowerShell as Administrator.
2.  Type the following command and press Enter:

curl -LO
https://storage.googleapis.com/minikube/releases/latest/minikube-installer.exe

3.  Install Minikube: .-installer.exe

STEP 3: START MINIKUBE

To start Minikube using Docker driver:

minikube start –driver=docker or minikube start

minikube status

docker login (open docker)

kubectl create deployment mynginx --image=nginx

kubectl get deployments

	kubectl get pods

kubectl describe pods

kubectl expose deployment mynginx --type=NodePort --port=80 --target-port=80

kubectl scale deployment mynginx --replicas=4

kubectl get service myngnix

kubectl port-forward svc/mynginx 8081:80

minikube tunnel
minikube service mynginx –url
 
Minikube dashboard
open url at brower
(nginx,kubernetes)

Stop and Clean Up
1.	Stop Nginx Deployment:

kubectl delete deployment mynginx
kubectl delete service mynginx
minikube stop
 minikube delete
 

Pull the Nagios Docker Image
•	Open a terminal and run:
  
      docker pull jasonrivers/nagios:latest


Run Nagios
•	Command:
docker run --name nagiosdemo -p 8888:80 jasonrivers/nagios:latest
 
•	Open your browser and navigate to:
http://localhost:8888
o	Login Credentials:
	Username: nagiosadmin
	Password: nagios
o	Once logged in, explore:
	Hosts: View systems being monitored local host:8888
open docker and see

Step 5: Stop and Remove Nagios
1.	Stop the Container:
o	Command:
docker stop nagiosdemo

2.	Delete the Container:
o	Command:
docker rm nagiosdemo

3.	Remove the Image (Optional):
o	List images:
docker images

o	Delete the Nagios image:
docker rmi jasonrivers/nagios:latest
 


//////////////

STEP 4: CHECK KUBECTL COMMAND

kubectl helps communicate with Kubernetes cluster.

Run: minikube kubectl – get pods -A

Or start dashboard: minikube dashboard

  -------------------------------------
  SECTION 2: DEPLOY NGINX IN MINIKUBE
  -------------------------------------

STEP 1: CREATE DEPLOYMENT

kubectl create deployment mynginx –image=nginx

Check deployments: kubectl get deployments

Check pods: kubectl get pods

STEP 2: EXPOSE NGINX SERVICE

kubectl expose deployment mynginx –type=NodePort –port=80
–target-port=80

STEP 3: SCALE PODS

kubectl scale deployment mynginx –replicas=4

STEP 4: ACCESS NGINX

Option 1: Port Forwarding: kubectl port-forward svc/mynginx 8081:80

Open browser: http://localhost:8081

Option 2 (if port-forward fails): minikube tunnel minikube service
mynginx –url

STEP 5: DELETE DEPLOYMENT & SERVICE

kubectl delete deployment mynginx kubectl delete service mynginx

STEP 6: STOP MINIKUBE

minikube stop

To delete cluster: minikube delete

  --------------------------------
  SECTION 3: NAGIOS USING DOCKER
  --------------------------------

STEP 1: PULL NAGIOS IMAGE

docker pull jasonrivers/nagios:latest

STEP 2: RUN NAGIOS CONTAINER

docker run –name nagiosdemo -p 8888:80 jasonrivers/nagios:latest

STEP 3: OPEN NAGIOS DASHBOARD

Open browser: http://localhost:8888

Login: Username: nagiosadmin Password: nagios

STEP 4: CHECK LOGS

docker logs -f nagiosdemo

STEP 5: STOP & REMOVE NAGIOS

docker stop nagiosdemo docker rm nagiosdemo docker rmi
jasonrivers/nagios:latest

  -------------------------------------------
  SECTION 4: AWS FREE TIER ACCOUNT CREATION
  -------------------------------------------

1.  Open: https://aws.amazon.com
2.  Click “Create AWS Account”
3.  Enter Email + Name
4.  Enter verification code from email
5.  Enter phone number for OTP verification
6.  Enter debit/credit card details (₹2 refundable charge)
7.  Choose “Basic Free Plan”
8.  Open AWS Console → Choose role: Academic / Researcher

  ----------------------------------------------
  SECTION 5: SBQ QUICK TROUBLESHOOTING ANSWERS
  ----------------------------------------------

1.  POD restarting repeatedly → check logs: kubectl logs

2.  POD stuck in Pending → not enough resources OR no nodes: kubectl
    describe pod

3.  Failed deployment → check events: kubectl describe deployment
    mynginx

4.  Pods failing health check: kubectl describe pod

5.  Rollback faulty deployment: kubectl rollout undo deployment/mynginx

6.  Debug running pod: kubectl exec -it – /bin/bash

7.  Expose service externally: kubectl expose deployment myapp
    –type=NodePort –port=80

8.  Start Nagios: docker start nagiosdemo

    Stop Nagios: docker stop nagiosdemo

9.  Nagios “Unable to connect to process”: docker restart nagiosdemo

10. Host not appearing in Nagios: nagios -v
    /usr/local/nagios/etc/nagios.cfg

11. Check Nagios running: docker ps

12. Real-time logs: docker logs -f nagiosdemo

13. Advantages:

-   Continuous monitoring
-   Alerts
-   Uptime stats
-   Plugin support
-   Open source

